        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The velocity resolution required to reach the science goals is 0.2km/s. Such a narrow resolution is required as most of the dense gas in these clouds are very cold (~10K) and have velocity dispersion that can be as small as a few tenths of a km/s. 

The dust continuum spectral window has a 2.8 km/s velocity resolution. The reason for chosing this one over the 89km/s resolution (and therefore decreasing the data rate) as to do with the legacy value of the project. Indeed, such spectral configuration will allow the detection of a large number of lines that can be used in the context of, for instance, astrochemistry projects in massive star forming regions. This is also why we set-up a second 1.9GHz continuum band with the same spectral resolution (and still remaining below the high data rate limit).
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The angular resolution required for this observation is 4". This is necessary since, at the distance of the targets, filaments have a typical width of 8". With 4" resolution we can therefore partially resolve the filaments and disentangle between emission ON the filaments and OFF the filaments. 

The targes are massive IRDCs. Because their average densities are high (&gt; few 10^4 cm^-3; cf Table 1 of the science jsutfication), both the N2H+(1-0) and HNC(1-0) emission extends over the entire clouds (&gt; 1 arcmin). Therefore, in order to be able to characterize as well as possible the velocity field along the filaments but also OFF the filaments, we need ACA and TP time. Even though it is time consuming, the sceince goals we defined will not be reached without ACA and TP observations. Only ALMA, at 3mm, can provide the necessary zero-spacing measurements for southern hemisphere sources down to a sensiviity of a tenth of a Kelvin.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We chose 0.1K (11.4mJy/beam) in a 0.2km/s channel as our rms N2H+(1-0) line sensitivity. This choice is based on our previous N2H+(1-0) observations of the SDC335 IRDC (Peretto et al. 2013). Such a sensitivity is required to obtain significant (&gt;3sigma) detection everywhere in the clouds. The 0.2km/s velocity resolution is also based on the narrowest emission we observed in such clouds which is about 0.6km/s in N2H+(1-0) (see also Peretto et al. 2014). The HNC(1-0) line is expected to be, on average over the clouds, as strong as N2H+(1-0) (see Miettinen 2014, A&amp;A, 562, 3). Therefore similar detections should be reached in this line, even though emission peaks might have different locations within the clouds. Note that the bandwith we chose is the smallest one cant set up for the spectral resolution we require.

In parallel to the line observations we want to obtain 5sigma detections on all massive (&gt;10 Msun) cores. At 2.5kpc distance (the average distance of our sample) such a core,with a temperature of 10K, and assuming a 3mm specific dust opacity of 8.7x10^-4 cm^2/g, has a flux of 0.62 mJy. A 5sigma detection on such core imply a rms dust continuum sensitivity of ~0.12 mJy. This is achieved simultaneously to the line osbervations by integrating the continuum emission over a 468 MHz spectral window.  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
